## 6. Firestore Security Rules

```javascript
rules_version = '2';
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    
    match /users/{userId} {
      allow read, write: if request.auth != null 
        && request.auth.token.email.matches('.*@nitgoa[.]ac[.]in$');
    }
    
    match /leave_requests/{docId} {
      allow read, delete: if true;
      allow create, update: if request.auth != null 
        && request.auth.token.email.matches('.*@nitgoa[.]ac[.]in$');
    }
    
    match /leave_history/{docId} {
      allow read, write: if request.auth != null 
        && request.auth.token.email.matches('.*@nitgoa[.]ac[.]in$');
    }
    
    match /gate_passes/{docId} {
      allow read, delete: if true;
      allow create, update: if request.auth != null 
        && request.auth.token.email.matches('.*@nitgoa[.]ac[.]in$');
    }
  }
}
```

### Why these rules:

| Collection | Public Read | Public Delete | Auth Write |
|-----------|------------|--------------|-----------|
| `users` | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ @nitgoa.ac.in only |
| `leave_requests` | ✅ (Security Portal) | ✅ (Security Portal) | ✅ @nitgoa.ac.in only |
| `leave_history` | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ @nitgoa.ac.in only |
| `gate_passes` | ✅ (Security Portal) | ✅ (Security Portal) | ✅ @nitgoa.ac.in only |

`gate_passes` and `leave_requests` allow public read/delete because the Security Portal app (used by guards) does not have authentication.

